{"type": "user", "message": {"role": "user", "content": [{"tool_use_id": "chatcmpl-tool-8c89cde9e9f09634", "type": "tool_result", "content": "1\t                                             A Diagnostic Evaluation Framework for AI-Generated Cover\n2\t                                                                       Songs\n3\t                                                   Using Music-Theoretic and Acoustic Features\n4\t                                                                             Yingxin Liang\n5\t                                                     Hangzhou Xiaoying Innovation Technology Co., Ltd. (Rythmix AI)\n6\t                                                                     yingxinliang.yxl@gmail.com\n7\t\n8\t\n9\t                                                                                         Abstract\n10\t                                                   AI-generated covers often fail through local musical errors that a global quality score\n11\t                                               cannot locate: the vocal contour may remain recognizable while the accompaniment uses\n12\t                                               the wrong harmonic function, or the output may stay in key while the arrangement remains\n13\t                                               incomplete. We present a five-dimensional diagnostic framework covering melodic pitch, har-\n14\tarXiv:2607.19688v1 [cs.SD] 22 Jul 2026\n15\t\n16\t\n17\t\n18\t\n19\t                                               monic progression, key consistency, style consistency, and arrangement/production quality.\n20\t                                               The benchmark contains 30 covers generated from 5 source songs by 6 systems, with expert\n21\t                                               severity ratings and 9 symbolic or acoustic features. Harmonic progression and arrange-\n22\t                                               ment had the highest severe-error rates (53% and 47%), whereas key consistency was better\n23\t                                               preserved. Six covers combined acceptable key consistency with severe harmonic errors.\n24\t                                               Large-leap ratio had a nominal association with melodic ratings (Spearman ρ = −0.429, un-\n25\t                                               corrected p = 0.018), but no feature correlation survived the nine-test multiplicity reference.\n26\t                                               An interpretable percentile-rule pilot likewise failed to outperform a fixed majority baseline\n27\t                                               reliably across 16 dimension-level comparisons. The results separate useful diagnostic ev-\n28\t                                               idence from dependable automatic scoring: low-level and symbolic summaries can expose\n29\t                                               particular symptoms, but they do not replace context-aware musical judgment.\n30\t\n31\t\n32\t                                         1    Introduction\n33\t                                         AI-generated cover songs are becoming increasingly capable of producing recognizable renditions\n34\t                                         of existing songs with changed timbre, genre, or production style. However, the resulting outputs\n35\t                                         often fail in ways that are difficult to diagnose with a single global quality score. A cover\n36\t                                         may follow the original vocal melody while using an implausible chord progression; it may\n37\t                                         remain broadly within the correct key while failing to realize the intended style; or it may\n38\t                                         sound loudness-normalized while still having an empty, unbalanced, or musically incomplete\n39\t                                         arrangement. In practice, this can produce a cover that does not sound simply “out of key”;\n40\t                                         the more specific problem is that the accompaniment does not know where the phrase is going.\n41\t                                         These are distinct musical failure modes, and collapsing them into one perceptual rating makes\n42\t                                         the resulting evaluation less useful for model analysis.\n43\t                                             This problem is especially important for cover-song generation because the task is reference-\n44\t                                         based. Unlike open-ended text-to-song generation, cover generation involves an existing song\n45\t                                         whose melody, tonality, harmonic expectations, and structure can be used as diagnostic anchors.\n46\t                                         This makes it possible to evaluate not only whether an output sounds good, but also where and\n47\t                                         how it deviates from the source or from the target style.\n48\t                                             Existing evaluation benchmarks for AI-generated music primarily focus on perception-level\n49\t                                         assessment of text-to-song outputs. SongBench [Wu et al., 2026] provides multi-dimensional\n50\t                                         quality scoring over large-scale generated song samples, while SongEval [Lei et al., 2025] evaluates\n51\t                                         aesthetic dimensions such as coherence, memorability, and musicality. These benchmarks are\n52\t\n53\t\n54\t                                                                                             1\n55\t\fvaluable for measuring overall listening quality, but they are not designed to localize music-\n56\ttheoretic errors in reference-based cover generation.\n57\t    Recent generation work has begun to encode explicit music-theoretic constraints. Decom-\n58\tposed chord-generation approaches, for example, separate retrieval, editing, and reranking to\n59\timprove harmonic feasibility. Yet evaluation still lacks a way to expose errors separately in\n60\tpitch, harmony, key stability, style, and arrangement.\n61\t    This paper addresses that gap through three contributions:\n62\t\n63\t    1. We propose a five-dimensional diagnostic taxonomy for AI-generated cover-song evalua-\n64\t       tion, covering melodic pitch accuracy, harmonic progression validity, key consistency, style\n65\t       consistency, and arrangement/production quality.\n66\t\n67\t    2. We construct a 30-sample diagnostic benchmark from 5 source songs and 6 generation\n68\t       systems, with severity-graded expert annotations and time-stamped error notes.\n69\t\n70\t    3. We test nine automatic features and an interpretable LOO rule pilot. Large-leap ratio\n71\t       has a nominal association with melodic judgments, but the rule system does not beat a\n72\t       fixed majority baseline reliably; the D3-high/D2-low cases further show why tonal stability\n73\t       cannot stand in for harmonic correctness.\n74\t\n75\t\n76\t2     Related Work\n77\tAI music evaluation benchmarks. Recent benchmarks have made AI-generated songs eas-\n78\tier to compare at scale, especially for text-to-song generation. SongBench [Wu et al., 2026] eval-\n79\tuates quality across dimensions including vocal quality, instrument quality, melody, structure,\n80\tarrangement, mixing, and musicality. SongEval [Lei et al., 2025] focuses on aesthetic dimensions\n81\tsuch as coherence, memorability, breath naturalness, structural clarity, and overall musical-\n82\tity. Concurrent work extends single-point MOS prediction with stem-aware cross-attention and\n83\tinterval-based uncertainty modeling for full-song aesthetics [Lv et al., 2026]. The present study\n84\tcomplements that learned scoring direction by testing where interpretable low-level and symbolic\n85\tfeatures fail to localize cover-specific musical errors. These approaches address listening-quality\n86\tassessment at scale, but they do not use a reference song to ask a more local diagnostic question:\n87\twhich part of the cover failed, and relative to what musical expectation?\n88\t\n89\tMusic-theoretic constraints in generation. Harmonic feasibility has also become a generation-\n90\tside concern. He et al. [2026], for example, propose a retrieval-edit-rerank framework for chord\n91\tgeneration that separates stylistic diversity from harmonic correctness. This is closely related to\n92\tthe present study because a generated cover may satisfy broad stylistic cues while still making\n93\tlocal harmonic decisions that contradict the melody or phrase function.\n94\t\n95\tCover song generation. Cover generation sits between preservation and transformation: the\n96\tsource melody, phrase structure, and tonal expectations should remain recognizable, while voice\n97\tidentity, genre, instrumentation, or arrangement style may change. SongEcho [Li et al., 2026]\n98\tapproaches cover-song generation through instance-adaptive element-wise linear modulation.\n99\tACE-Step and ACE-Step 1.5 [Gong et al., 2025, 2026] provide a broader music generation\n100\tfoundation model and conditioning extensions, including SA ControlNet and MuseControlLite.\n101\tThe resulting outputs are therefore not well described by a single “good/bad” score; they require\n102\tevaluation that can separate preserved elements from newly introduced errors.\n103\t\n104\tAudio quality assessment and MIR tools. The MIR and audio-engineering toolchain\n105\tprovides useful evidence, but its scope is uneven. ITU-R BS.1770-4 defines integrated loudness\n106\tmeasurement, while MUSHRA (ITU-R BS.1534) provides a subjective evaluation protocol for\n107\t\n108\t                                                 2\n109\t\faudio quality. Demucs [Défossez, 2021], Basic Pitch [Bittner et al., 2022], pretty_midi [Raffel and\n110\tEllis, 2014], music21 [Cuthbert and Ariza, 2010], librosa [McFee et al., 2015], and pyloudnorm\n111\t[Steinmetz, 2019] make it possible to extract source-separated stems, symbolic pitch features,\n112\tpitch-class evidence, loudness measures, and spectral descriptors. The open question is not\n113\twhether these features are useful, but where they stop being sufficient: they can describe parts\n114\tof the signal, but may not capture whether an arrangement actually works as music.\n115\t\n116\t\n117\t3     Evaluation Framework\n118\t3.1   Diagnostic Dimensions\n119\tThe proposed framework evaluates AI-generated cover songs across five diagnostic dimensions.\n120\tEach dimension corresponds to a different type of musical adequacy and is intended to localize\n121\tthe source of quality degradation.\n122\t\n123\tD1: Melodic Pitch Accuracy. This dimension measures whether the generated vocal melody\n124\tpreserves the intended pitch contour and avoids salient wrong notes. Evidence includes vocal\n125\tMIDI transcription, pitch-contour inspection, and large-leap ratio. Severe D1 failures include\n126\tout-of-tune vocal lines, incorrect melodic intervals, octave displacement that changes melodic\n127\tidentity, or unstable pitch tracking that disrupts the recognizability of the source melody.\n128\t\n129\tD2: Harmonic Progression Validity. This dimension measures whether the accompani-\n130\tment follows a coherent harmonic progression and avoids non-functional or contextually inap-\n131\tpropriate chord changes. Evidence includes chromagram visualization and time-stamped expert\n132\tannotations identifying specific harmonic errors. Severe D2 failures include chords that con-\n133\ttradict the expected function of a phrase, incorrect cadential harmony, or accompaniment that\n134\tremains in a nominal key but fails to support the melody.\n135\t\n136\tD3: Key Consistency. This dimension measures whether the generated cover maintains a\n137\tstable or musically justified key center. Evidence includes key confidence, key-change rate, in-\n138\tkey note ratio, and chroma-based views. D3 differs from D2: a sample can stay in one key while\n139\tstill using poor chord progressions, and this distinction is central to the framework.\n140\t\n141\tD4: Style Consistency. This dimension measures whether the generated cover matches the\n142\ttarget style prompt in instrumentation, rhythm, harmonic language, texture, and overall musical\n143\tcharacter. Evidence comes from expert comparison between the intended style prompt and the\n144\tgenerated output. No computational metric is assigned to D4 because genre and style matching\n145\trequire semantic understanding of musical conventions rather than only signal-level analysis.\n146\t\n147\tD5: Arrangement and Production Quality. This dimension measures whether instru-\n148\tmentation, texture, balance, timbre, structure, and production quality support the intended\n149\tcover. Evidence comes primarily from expert annotation, with loudness and spectral features\n150\treported as low-level reference indicators. Severe D5 failures include incomplete instrumenta-\n151\ttion, poor vocal–instrument balance, distorted timbre, empty texture, or structurally incoherent\n152\tarrangement.\n153\t\n154\t3.2   Severity Grading\n155\tEach dimension is rated on a 5-point scale. For analysis, the scores are grouped into three\n156\tseverity levels (Table 1).\n157\t\n158\t\n159\t\n160\t                                                3\n161\t\f                                Table 1: Severity grading scheme.\n162\t\n163\t                Severity       Score   Meaning\n164\t                Acceptable      4–5    No salient error, or only minor issues that\n165\t                                       do not affect musical coherence\n166\t                Minor issue      3     Perceptible issue, but the cover remains\n167\t                                       musically usable\n168\t                Severe issue    1–2    Error affects musical coherence, recogniz-\n169\t                                       ability, or user experience\n170\t\n171\t\n172\t    This severity grouping is designed to make the framework useful for both research analysis\n173\tand practical model diagnosis. The exact numerical score captures relative quality, while the\n174\tseverity grouping identifies whether a failure would likely matter to listeners or downstream\n175\tproduct use.\n176\t\n177\t3.3   Annotation Protocol\n178\tThe first author, who has absolute pitch, formal music-theory training, and professional ex-\n179\tperience evaluating AI-generated music systems at an AI music product company, performed\n180\tall annotations. For each sample, the first author assigned five dimension scores and recorded\n181\ttime-stamped diagnostic notes describing the specific musical errors. The notes identify affected\n182\tmusical elements where applicable, including melodic deviations, chord errors, key changes, style\n183\tmismatches, and arrangement or production defects.\n184\t    To check rating stability, the first author re-annotated six samples (20%) after a one-week\n185\tinterval. We treat this exercise as a procedural consistency check rather than a reliability\n186\testimate and do not report a formal agreement coefficient.\n187\t    The use of a single expert annotator limits inter-rater reliability analysis, but the annotation\n188\tprotocol was designed to improve transparency: each low score must be supported by an explicit\n189\tmusical description and, where possible, a time-stamped location in the audio. This makes the\n190\tbenchmark auditable and provides a basis for future multi-annotator validation.\n191\t\n192\t\n193\t4     Dataset\n194\t4.1   Source Songs\n195\tFive source songs were selected to cover different musical conditions, including pop ballad, rock,\n196\telectronic, and harmonically varied mixed-genre material. The selection criteria were: (a) the\n197\tevaluator could manually verify the source melody, chord progression, and key centers; (b) the set\n198\tincluded both relatively simple diatonic progressions and more complex harmonic materials; and\n199\t(c) the songs varied in tempo, vocal range, texture, and structural complexity. The purpose of\n200\tthe source-song set is not to represent all popular music, but to provide a controlled exploratory\n201\tbenchmark for testing whether the diagnostic framework can distinguish different failure modes.\n202\t\n203\t4.2   Generation Models\n204\tSix generation systems were evaluated (Table 2). Each source song was processed by all 6\n205\tsystems, producing 30 generated cover samples. All samples were generated with style prompts\n206\tspecifying target genre, instrumentation, and vocal characteristics. Because the systems differ\n207\tin interface, controllability, and post-processing behavior, the benchmark is best interpreted as a\n208\tdiagnostic comparison of output behavior rather than a controlled architecture-level comparison.\n209\t\n210\t\n211\t\n212\t                                                 4\n213\t\f                      Table 2: Generation systems evaluated in this study.\n214\t\n215\t                 Model               Description\n216\t                 SongEcho            Instance-adaptive cover generation via ELM\n217\t                 ACE-Step+SA         ACE-Step 1.5 with SA ControlNet + LoRA\n218\t                 ACE-Step+MCL        ACE-Step 1.5 with MuseControlLite\n219\t                 ACE-Step            ACE-Step 1.5 base model\n220\t                 MiniMax             Commercial music generation API\n221\t                 Mureka              Commercial music generation API\n222\t\n223\t\n224\t4.3    Data Availability\n225\tDue to copyright constraints on source songs and licensing terms of commercial APIs, the full\n226\taudio set cannot be released without restrictions. We therefore release the annotation schema,\n227\textracted features, anonymized diagnostic metadata, and analysis pipeline. Audio excerpts are\n228\tprovided only where licensing permits.\n229\t\n230\t\n231\t5     Computational Methods\n232\t5.1    Pipeline\n233\tEach generated cover sample was processed through the following pipeline:\n234\t\n235\t    1. Source separation. Demucs (htdemucs_ft, two-stem mode) separates each cover into\n236\t       vocal and accompaniment stems.\n237\t\n238\t    2. Vocal transcription. Basic Pitch transcribes the separated vocal stem into MIDI, pro-\n239\t       ducing note-level pitch, onset, and offset information. The resulting MIDI files are parsed\n240\t       with pretty_midi for pitch-interval and range features, and with music21 for pitch-class\n241\t       and key-related analyses.\n242\t\n243\t    3. Feature extraction. Nine features are computed from the separated stems, vocal MIDI\n244\t       transcription, and full audio mixture. librosa is used for spectral-contrast analysis, while\n245\t       pyloudnorm is used for loudness and loudness-range measurements.\n246\t\n247\t    This pipeline is designed to provide diagnostic evidence rather than fully automatic scoring.\n248\tThe features are used to test whether low-level or symbolic measurements align with expert\n249\tratings.\n250\t\n251\t5.2    Feature Definitions\n252\tD1-related features from vocal MIDI. Large-Leap Ratio (LLR): Proportion of adjacent\n253\tnote intervals exceeding 7 semitones. Higher values indicate more melodically implausible jumps.\n254\tPitch Range (PR): Difference between the maximum and minimum transcribed vocal pitch, in\n255\tsemitones. PR is reported for reference and may be inflated by transcription artifacts. Pitch\n256\tStability (PS): Standard deviation of adjacent-note interval sizes. Higher values indicate more\n257\tirregular intervallic behavior.\n258\t\n259\tD2/D3-related features from vocal MIDI and chroma representations. In-Key Note\n260\tRatio (IKNR): Proportion of transcribed vocal notes whose pitch classes belong to the detected\n261\tglobal key’s diatonic scale. The global key is estimated using the Krumhansl–Schmuckler key-\n262\tfinding algorithm implemented in music21. Key Confidence (KC): Correlation between the\n263\t\n264\t\n265\t                                                   5\n266\t\fobserved pitch-class distribution and the best-matching key template. Higher values indicate a\n267\tmore clearly defined tonal center. Key-Change Rate (KCR): Proportion of adjacent 10-second\n268\twindows where the independently detected key changes. Higher values indicate less stable tonal-\n269\tity.\n270\t\n271\tD5-related features from the full mixture. Loudness Deviation (LUFS_dev): Absolute\n272\tdifference between integrated loudness and a reference level of −12 LUFS, computed using\n273\tpyloudnorm following ITU-R BS.1770-4. The deviation is reported in LU. Loudness Range\n274\t(LRA): Dynamic range in Loudness Units, computed from the stereo signal. Spectral Contrast\n275\t(SC): Mean spectral contrast across all frequency bands and time frames, computed using librosa\n276\tfrom a mono downmix.\n277\t\n278\t5.3   Excluded Features\n279\tNo automatic chord-recognition metric is used for D2. Available chord-recognition outputs were\n280\tnot sufficiently reliable for diagnostic evaluation of generated covers, especially when source\n281\tseparation artifacts, dense textures, or distorted timbres were present. A noisy chord-recognition\n282\tmetric would risk converting tool errors into false evidence about model behavior. D2 is therefore\n283\tevaluated through time-stamped expert annotation, supported by chromagram inspection rather\n284\tthan automatic chord labels.\n285\t    No computational metric is used for D4. Style consistency depends on genre conventions, in-\n286\tstrumentation choices, rhythmic feel, and semantic alignment with the prompt. These properties\n287\tare not adequately represented by the low-level features used in this study.\n288\t\n289\t5.4   Known Limitations of the Pipeline\n290\tBasic Pitch transcription can introduce errors from instrumental bleed, octave confusion, or\n291\tunstable vocal separation. These artifacts can affect PR, LLR, and PS. For this reason, the\n292\tcomputational features are interpreted as supporting evidence rather than ground-truth mea-\n293\tsurements. Rank-order correlations are reported as exploratory statistics and should be validated\n294\ton larger datasets with improved transcription and additional annotators.\n295\t\n296\t5.5   Rule-Based Diagnostic Pilot\n297\tWe tested whether the extracted features could support a transparent rule-based diagnostic\n298\trather than only correlational analysis. Expert ratings were collapsed into three severity classes:\n299\tratings 4–5 were coded as acceptable (0), rating 3 as minor (1), and ratings 1–2 as severe (2).\n300\tFor each metric–dimension pair, two candidate cutpoints were estimated from the training data:\n301\ta severity-2 quartile (the lower quartile for higher-is-worse metrics and the upper quartile for\n302\tlower-is-worse metrics) and the severity-1 median. Small-sample overlap can reverse their raw\n303\torder, so the pair was ordered by the known metric direction before assigning yellow and red\n304\tdecision regions. A programmatic assertion enforced yellow < red for higher-is-worse metrics\n305\t(LLR, PS, KCR, and LUFS_dev) and yellow > red for lower-is-worse metrics (IKNR, KC, LRA,\n306\tand SC) in every validation fold. The archived JSON retains both raw candidates and ordered\n307\tcutpoints (see Appendix A).\n308\t    Metrics were mapped to D1 (LLR and PS), D2 (IKNR as a deliberately coarse tonal proxy\n309\trather than a chord-function measure), D3 (IKNR, KC, and KCR), and D5 (LUFS_dev, LRA,\n310\tand SC). Each metric cast an acceptable, yellow, or red vote. A dimension was labeled severe\n311\twhen a strict majority of its metrics cast red votes, minor when a strict majority cast at least\n312\tyellow votes, and acceptable otherwise. D4 was excluded because style consistency requires\n313\tsemantic comparison with the target prompt and is not represented by the available low-level\n314\tor symbolic features.\n315\t\n316\t\n317\t                                                6\n318\t\f               Table 3: Mean expert ratings by model (n = 5 songs per model).\n319\t\n320\t                     Model               D1     D2    D3    D4    D5     Mean\n321\t                     MiniMax             4.8    4.0   4.8   3.2   3.6     4.1\n322\t                     Mureka              4.2    3.8   4.6   4.6   3.6     4.2\n323\t                     ACE-Step            2.8    2.0   4.2   4.2   2.6     3.2\n324\t                     SongEcho            3.6    2.8   3.4   2.4   2.6     3.0\n325\t                     ACE-Step+SA         2.6    1.4   3.0   1.6   1.6     2.0\n326\t                     ACE-Step+MCL        1.2    1.0   1.2   1.4   1.2     1.2\n327\t\n328\t\n329\t    Thresholds were evaluated by leave-one-out (LOO) validation: each fold learned cutpoints\n330\tfrom 29 generated covers and applied them to the held-out cover. We evaluated the three-class\n331\ttask and a binary task that grouped acceptable and minor cases against severe cases. Accuracy\n332\tand weighted F1 were compared with a majority-class baseline. For bootstrap comparisons, the\n333\tbaseline was fixed to the full-sample majority class for each dimension and setting and was not\n334\trecomputed within resamples. Defining the baseline on the full sample can slightly favor it; we\n335\tretain that convention to match the reported baseline and state it explicitly.\n336\t    Uncertainty was estimated with 10,000 paired generated-sample-level bootstrap draws and\n337\ta fixed random seed. Each draw sampled 30 filenames with replacement, and the same indices\n338\twere applied to rule and baseline predictions. Descriptive overall summaries carried all four\n339\tdiagnostic dimensions for each selected filename instead of resampling the 120 dimension rows\n340\tindependently. We report percentile 95% intervals for ∆ = rule−baseline and two-sided p-values\n341\tcomputed as 2 min[P (∆ > 0), P (∆ < 0)]. Weighted F1 used zero_division=0 when a resample\n342\tomitted a class.\n343\t\n344\t\n345\t6     Results\n346\t6.1   Expert Rating Summary\n347\tTable 3 shows the mean expert ratings per model across the five diagnostic dimensions.\n348\t    MiniMax and Mureka achieved the highest overall ratings. ACE-Step+MCL produced se-\n349\tvere failures in 3 of 5 songs, with all five dimensions scored 1 in those cases. ACE-Step base\n350\thad relatively high key and style ratings (D3 = 4.2, D4 = 4.2) but much lower harmony and\n351\tarrangement ratings (D2 = 2.0, D5 = 2.6). Broad tonal or stylistic plausibility therefore did not\n352\tguarantee functional harmony or a complete arrangement.\n353\t\n354\t6.2   Severity Distribution\n355\tTable 4 shows the proportion of ratings at each severity level by dimension.\n356\t\n357\t                Table 4: Severity distribution by dimension (n = 30 samples).\n358\t\n359\t                Dimension          Acceptable (4–5)     Minor (3)       Severe (1–2)\n360\t                D1 Melody                 47%               23%            30%\n361\t                D2 Harmony                23%               23%            53%\n362\t                D3 Key                    63%                7%            30%\n363\t                D4 Style                  37%               17%            47%\n364\t                D5 Arrangement            23%               30%            47%\n365\t\n366\t    D2 had the highest severe-error rate (53%), followed by D4 and D5 (47% each). D3 was\n367\tthe best-preserved dimension, with 63% of samples rated acceptable. This distribution indicates\n368\t\n369\t                                                7\n370\t\f                      Model-by-dimension diagnostic ratings\n371\t                                                                                5.0\n372\t               MiniMax     4.8      4.0       4.8      3.2      3.6\n373\t                                                                                4.5\n374\t                Mureka     4.2      3.8       4.6      4.6      3.6             4.0\n375\t\n376\t\n377\t\n378\t\n379\t                                                                                   Mean expert rating\n380\t                                                                                3.5\n381\t              ACE-Step     2.8      2.0       4.2      4.2      2.6\n382\t                                                                                3.0\n383\t             SongEcho      3.6      2.8       3.4      2.4      2.6\n384\t                                                                                2.5\n385\t          ACE-Step+SA      2.6      1.4       3.0      1.6      1.6             2.0\n386\t                                                                                1.5\n387\t        ACE-Step+MCL       1.2      1.0       1.2      1.4      1.2\n388\t                                                                                1.0\n389\t                           D1       D2        D3       D4        D5\n390\t                          Melody Harmony      Key     Style Arrangement\n391\t\n392\tFigure 1: Model-by-dimension heatmap. Each cell shows the mean expert rating for one model\n393\tand one diagnostic dimension. MiniMax and Mureka retain relatively high ratings across most\n394\tdimensions, ACE-Step base shows the D3-high/D2-low asymmetry at the model level, and ACE-\n395\tStep+MCL fails consistently across dimensions.\n396\t\n397\t\n398\tthat the evaluated systems more often preserve a tonal center than produce coherent chord\n399\tprogressions, accurate style realization, or complete arrangements.\n400\t    The score distribution had substantial mass at both endpoints: 26% of the 150 dimension\n401\tratings were 1 and 22% were 5. Moderate ratings were less dominant than clear successes or\n402\tsubstantial failures.\n403\t\n404\t6.3   Inter-Dimension Correlations\n405\tAll ten pairwise inter-dimension Spearman correlations had uncorrected p < 0.01, ranging from\n406\tρ = 0.507 for D1–D4 to ρ = 0.799 for D3–D5 (see Table 8 in Appendix B for the full matrix).\n407\tWe treat these comparisons as exploratory and make no familywise significance claim. The\n408\tconsistently positive associations show that failure modes often co-occur: covers with poor\n409\tmelody accuracy also tended to score poorly on harmony, style, or arrangement.\n410\t    Co-occurrence does not make the dimensions interchangeable. Six of the 30 covers had D3 ≥\n411\t4 but D2 ≤ 2: the tonal center remained plausible while the chord progression contained severe\n412\terrors. Those cases show that a model can preserve surface-level tonality without generating\n413\tfunctional harmony inside that tonal space.\n414\t\n415\t6.4   Feature–Rating Correlations\n416\tTable 5 shows the nine prespecified Spearman correlations. The p-values are exploratory and\n417\tuncorrected. A Bonferroni reference threshold for nine comparisons is 0.0056; no feature reaches\n418\tit.\n419\t\n420\t                                               8\n421\t\f                                                          Key consistency versus harmonic progression validity\n422\t                                                  5                                                                    Highlighted covers\n423\t                                                                                                                       1 ACE / Song1\n424\t                                                                                                                       2 ACE+SA / Song2\n425\t                                                                                                                       3 SongEcho / Song2\n426\t                                                                                                                       4 ACE / Song3\n427\t                                                                                                                       5 ACE / Song4\n428\t                                                                                                                       6 ACE+SA / Song4\n429\t\n430\t\n431\t              D2: Harmonic Progression Validity\n432\t                                                  4\n433\t\n434\t\n435\t                                                  3\n436\t\n437\t\n438\t                                                  2                                                  1           3 4\n439\t\n440\t\n441\t\n442\t                                                          Other samples\n443\t                                                  1       D3 4 and D2     2                         5 6           2\n444\t\n445\t                                                      1              2                 3            4            5\n446\t                                                                              D3: Key Consistency\n447\t\n448\tFigure 2: D3 versus D2 sample-level scatter plot. Each point represents one generated cover\n449\tsample. The lower-right diagnostic region corresponds to samples with acceptable key consis-\n450\ttency but severe harmonic-progression errors (D3 ≥ 4 and D2 ≤ 2). A small deterministic jitter\n451\tis applied to overlapping points for visualization only; all ratings remain integer-valued.\n452\t\n453\tTable 5: Spearman correlations between features and expert ratings (n = 30; p-values un-\n454\tcorrected). In the Expected Dir. column, ✓ indicates that the observed sign matches the\n455\thypothesized direction and × indicates that it does not.\n456\t\n457\t                          Dim.                            Feature                    ρ          p   Sig.          Expected Dir.\n458\t                          D1                              LLR             −0.429          0.018     nominal *     negative ✓\n459\t                          D1                              PS              −0.013          0.947     n.s.          negative ✓\n460\t                          D2                              IKNR            +0.136          0.475     n.s.          positive ✓\n461\t                          D3                              KC              +0.300          0.107     n.s.          positive ✓\n462\t                          D3                              IKNR            +0.263          0.161     n.s.          positive ✓\n463\t                          D3                              KCR             −0.296          0.112     n.s.          negative ✓\n464\t                          D5                              LUFS_dev        +0.294          0.115     n.s.          negative ×\n465\t                          D5                              LRA             −0.039          0.840     n.s.          positive ×\n466\t                          D5                              SC              +0.040          0.832     n.s.          positive ✓\n467\t\n468\t\n469\tD1: Large melodic leaps show a nominal association with expert ratings. LLR\n470\tcorrelated negatively with D1 (ρ = −0.429, uncorrected p = 0.018): covers with more large\n471\tjumps in the transcribed vocal line tended to receive lower melodic ratings. The association\n472\tdoes not survive the nine-test multiplicity reference and is therefore treated as a feature-level\n473\tlead, not validated construct evidence.\n474\t    PS did not correlate with D1 despite also measuring interval behavior. LLR counts specific\n475\tlarge-interval violations, whereas PS measures general interval variability, which can be high\n476\tin stylistically varied but acceptable melodies. The ratings were more closely associated with\n477\tsalient implausible leaps than with general interval variance.\n478\t\n479\tD2/D3: Key-related features are weak proxies. D2 IKNR was small (ρ = 0.136, p =\n480\t0.475). KC, IKNR, and KCR for D3 moved in the expected directions, but none reached\n481\tuncorrected p < 0.05. At n = 30, these values do not establish reliable automatic indicators,\n482\tand IKNR in particular cannot measure chord function.\n483\t\n484\t\n485\t                                                                                            9\n486\t\fTable 6: Rule-based diagnostic accuracy versus fixed majority-class baseline. ∆ is rule minus\n487\tbaseline; confidence intervals and p-values come from 10,000 paired generated-sample-level boot-\n488\tstrap draws.\n489\t\n490\t           Dim.    Setting   Rule Acc.    Base Acc.         ∆   95% CI                p\n491\t           D1      3-class        0.433       0.467    −0.033   [−0.233, 0.167] 0.605\n492\t           D2      3-class        0.433       0.533    −0.100   [−0.333, 0.167] 0.368\n493\t           D3      3-class        0.433       0.633    −0.200   [−0.433, 0.067] 0.089\n494\t           D5      3-class        0.300       0.467    −0.167   [−0.400, 0.067] 0.128\n495\t           D1      Binary         0.600       0.700    −0.100   [−0.233, 0.033] 0.086\n496\t           D2      Binary         0.567       0.533    +0.033   [−0.267, 0.300] 0.733\n497\t           D3      Binary         0.767       0.700    +0.067   [−0.100, 0.233] 0.303\n498\t           D5      Binary         0.433       0.533    −0.100   [−0.333, 0.133] 0.327\n499\t\n500\t\n501\tD5: Low-level acoustic features do not explain arrangement quality. LUFS_dev,\n502\tLRA, and SC did not meaningfully correlate with D5 ratings, and LUFS_dev moved opposite\n503\tto the expected direction. Loudness normalization mainly reflects post-processing: a cover can\n504\tsit near the target loudness while retaining poor instrumentation, weak texture, or unnatu-\n505\tral timbre. Arrangement evaluation therefore needs musical and timbral relations that these\n506\tsummary statistics omit.\n507\t\n508\t6.5   Rule-Based Diagnostic Pilot\n509\tTable 6 reports the accuracy comparison against the fixed majority-class baseline. The three-\n510\tclass rules did not beat the baseline on any dimension. Binary severe-error detection was direc-\n511\ttionally better for D2 and D3, but the paired intervals remained wide at n = 30.\n512\t    Across the 16 dimension-level comparisons, every 95% interval crossed zero and no un-\n513\tcorrected two-sided p-value was below 0.05. The largest positive trends occurred for binary\n514\tweighted F1 on D2 (∆ = 0.188, 95% CI [−0.125, 0.473], p = 0.232) and D3 (∆ = 0.175, 95% CI\n515\t[−0.017, 0.375], p = 0.072), but neither supports a confirmed improvement. In the descriptive\n516\tpooled summary, three-class accuracy was lower for the rule system than for the baseline (0.400\n517\tvs. 0.525; ∆ = −0.125, 95% CI [−0.233, −0.017], nominal p = 0.023). This pooled value is not\n518\ttreated as an independent dimension-level test. The 16 dimension-level p-values are reported\n519\twithout multiplicity adjustment for transparency; under a Bonferroni reference threshold of\n520\t0.05/16 = 0.0031, no comparison would survive correction. This statement is included to avoid\n521\tselective interpretation of nominal trends.\n522\t    Global percentile thresholds discard musical context. IKNR cannot distinguish functional\n523\tharmony from scale membership; key-confidence statistics cannot determine whether a local\n524\tmodulation is intentional; loudness and spectral summaries do not represent instrumentation,\n525\ttexture, or arrangement completeness. Even the nominal D1–LLR association did not produce\n526\treliable threshold classification against the baseline. The binary D3 result leaves open a possible\n527\tuse for coarse severe-error flags, but the present evidence does not support naive thresholding\n528\tas a standalone evaluator.\n529\t\n530\t6.6   Illustrative Cases\n531\tCase A: Complete success. MiniMax, Song 3, scored 5/5/5/5/5. The melody contour\n532\twas natural and accurate, harmonic progressions were coherent, key was stable, the output\n533\tmatched the style prompt, and the arrangement showed appropriate timbre, groove, balance,\n534\tand completeness.\n535\t\n536\t\n537\t\n538\t                                                10\n539\t\f                                            Paired bootstrap diagnostic deltas\n540\t            3-class | accuracy | D1\n541\t            3-class | accuracy | D2\n542\t            3-class | accuracy | D3\n543\t            3-class | accuracy | D5\n544\t        3-class | weighted F1 | D1\n545\t        3-class | weighted F1 | D2\n546\t        3-class | weighted F1 | D3\n547\t        3-class | weighted F1 | D5\n548\t             binary | accuracy | D1\n549\t             binary | accuracy | D2\n550\t             binary | accuracy | D3\n551\t             binary | accuracy | D5\n552\t         binary | weighted F1 | D1\n553\t         binary | weighted F1 | D2\n554\t         binary | weighted F1 | D3\n555\t         binary | weighted F1 | D5\n556\t                                      0.4   0.2                 0.0               0.2   0.4\n557\t                                                       (rule - majority baseline)\n558\t\n559\tFigure 3: Paired-bootstrap rule-minus-baseline differences. Points show observed differences in\n560\taccuracy or weighted F1 , horizontal lines show 95% paired-bootstrap intervals, and the vertical\n561\tline marks zero. The plot contains the 16 dimension-level comparisons (4 dimensions × 2 settings\n562\t× 2 metrics); aggregate overall summaries are excluded.\n563\t\n564\t\n565\tCase B: Complete failure. ACE-Step+MCL, Song 1, scored 1/1/1/1/1. The output was\n566\tout of tune, harmonically incoherent, and arrangement-deficient, with only drums clearly audible\n567\tand severe timbral distortion in the remaining instrumentation.\n568\t\n569\tCase C: Asymmetric failure. ACE-Step, Song 3, scored 4/2/5/5/2. The melody was plau-\n570\tsible and the key was stable, but the accompaniment used B♭ at 0:22–0:24 and 0:49–0:51 where\n571\tthe source progression uses G as the dominant resolving toward C minor. B♭ is diatonic to\n572\tC minor, but in these phrases it replaced the source song’s functional dominant resolution. The\n573\tarrangement was also sparse and poorly balanced. A single global score would obscure this\n574\tprofile: the output was not uniformly bad, but its harmonic and arrangement failures would be\n575\thighly relevant for model debugging.\n576\t\n577\t\n578\t7     Discussion\n579\t7.1   Diagnostic Evaluation Reveals Non-Uniform Failure\n580\tFailures were not evenly distributed across musical dimensions. Harmonic progression and ar-\n581\trangement quality produced the most severe ratings, while key consistency was relatively pre-\n582\tserved. The evaluated systems more often maintained a broad tonal center than a functional\n583\tchord progression or complete arrangement.\n584\t\n585\t7.2   Key Consistency Is Not Harmonic Correctness\n586\tKey consistency is not a proxy for harmonic correctness. D3 measures tonal stability, whereas D2\n587\tasks whether the chord sequence functions coherently within that center. The six D3-high/D2-\n588\tlow covers show that a cover can remain broadly “in key” while its harmonies fail to support the\n589\t\n590\t\n591\t                                                  11\n592\t\fmelody or phrase structure.\n593\t    Pitch-class distributions and tonal-center cues therefore provide incomplete training targets.\n594\tA system may remain in C minor without learning when a dominant, subdominant, or chromatic\n595\talteration is contextually appropriate. Symbolic chord conditioning and phrase-level harmonic\n596\tplanning address that missing relation more directly.\n597\t\n598\t7.3   Automatic Features Capture Only Part of Expert Judgment\n599\tThe feature correlations and rule-based pilot show the limits of the present representation. LLR\n600\tremains interpretable because unusually large vocal leaps are concrete and inspectable, but\n601\tits association with D1 did not produce a threshold classifier that reliably beat the majority\n602\tbaseline. Correlation with an expert score is therefore not sufficient evidence that a feature can\n603\tserve as an automatic decision rule.\n604\t    The negative result is stronger for D2 and D5. IKNR describes scale membership, not chord\n605\tfunction, while loudness, dynamic range, and spectral contrast describe signal distributions\n606\trather than whether a bass line supports the harmony, an instrument timbre matches the in-\n607\ttended style, or an arrangement is structurally complete. Thresholding these summaries cannot\n608\trecover the missing musical relations. Their proper role in the current framework is supporting\n609\tevidence for expert diagnosis, not replacement of expert judgment.\n610\t\n611\t7.4   Implications for Evaluation and Product Use\n612\tGlobal ratings should be supplemented with diagnostic dimensions. A moderate average can\n613\thide a consequential failure pattern, such as preserved melody paired with unusable harmony.\n614\t   For product evaluation, the dimensions also separate recoverable defects from failures that\n615\trequire regeneration. Minor loudness or balance problems may respond to post-processing; severe\n616\tharmonic errors usually require a new generation or a model-level correction.\n617\t\n618\t7.5   Future Work: Learned Representations Rather Than Threshold Tuning\n619\tThe pilot rules were intentionally simple and interpretable. Their failure to outperform the\n620\tmajority baseline reliably rules out further cutpoint tuning as a useful direction for this dataset.\n621\tWith only 30 covers, threshold optimization, ad hoc feature selection, or a small supervised\n622\tclassifier would mostly fit the benchmark’s noise.\n623\t    Future models need representations that preserve musical context: temporal embeddings\n624\trelating melody to accompaniment, chord- and phrase-aware representations for harmonic func-\n625\ttion, and audio-text or style embeddings for D4. Training and testing them will require a larger\n626\tmulti-annotator corpus with held-out source songs. The current benchmark defines the failure\n627\tmodes but is too small for that model-development stage.\n628\t\n629\t\n630\t8     Limitations\n631\tSingle annotator. All expert ratings were assigned by the first author. Although the first\n632\tauthor has absolute pitch, formal music-theory training, and professional AI-music evaluation\n633\texperience, inter-rater reliability cannot be assessed in the current version. The six-sample\n634\trepeat annotation was a procedural consistency check, not a substitute for independent raters.\n635\tThe time-stamped annotation protocol improves transparency, but future work should include\n636\tmultiple annotators and agreement analysis.\n637\t\n638\tSmall sample size. The benchmark contains 30 samples from 5 songs and 6 systems. This\n639\tis sufficient for an exploratory diagnostic study, but it limits statistical power. Feature–rating\n640\t\n641\t\n642\t\n643\t                                                12\n644\t\fcorrelations should therefore be interpreted as preliminary evidence rather than definitive metric\n645\tvalidation.\n646\t\n647\tSource-song clustering. The 30 generated covers are grouped within 5 source songs, so\n648\toutputs derived from the same source may share difficulty, structure, or genre effects. The\n649\tpaired bootstrap resamples generated-cover filenames, not source-song clusters. With only five\n650\tclusters, cluster-bootstrap inference would itself be unstable; larger studies should sample more\n651\tsource songs and treat source identity as the primary resampling unit.\n652\t\n653\tTranscription artifacts. Basic Pitch transcription may introduce octave errors, false notes,\n654\tor artifacts from instrumental bleed. These issues can affect pitch-derived features, especially\n655\tPR and PS. The study therefore treats computational features as auxiliary evidence rather than\n656\tas ground truth.\n657\t\n658\tNo direct automatic D2 or D4 metric. Harmonic progression validity and style consistency\n659\tare not represented by direct automatic measures. The pilot uses IKNR only as a deliberately\n660\tweak D2 tonal proxy, not as a measure of chord function. This is a deliberate design choice:\n661\tunreliable chord recognition or genre matching could produce misleading evidence. Future work\n662\tshould investigate more robust symbolic and learned representations for these dimensions.\n663\t\n664\tLimited genre coverage. Five source songs cannot represent the diversity of popular music,\n665\tharmonic language, production style, or cultural listening expectations. Broader claims require\n666\ta larger and more varied source set.\n667\t\n668\t\n669\t9    Conclusion\n670\tThis paper presented a five-dimensional diagnostic evaluation framework for AI-generated cover\n671\tsongs. Applied to 30 generated covers from 5 songs and 6 systems, the framework shows that the\n672\tmost frequent severe failures are not simply surface-level audio defects, but harmonic-progression\n673\tand arrangement failures. Key consistency is comparatively better preserved.\n674\t    The automatic analyses produced a narrower result than the feature correlations alone might\n675\timply. Large-leap ratio had a nominal relationship with melodic ratings, yet neither it nor the\n676\tother features yielded rule-based decisions that reliably beat the majority baseline. Key sum-\n677\tmaries omit harmonic function, and loudness or spectral summaries omit arrangement structure.\n678\t    AI cover evaluation must distinguish tonal stability from harmonic correctness and signal\n679\tquality from musical coherence. A cover can remain in key while making locally wrong harmonic\n680\tdecisions. Diagnostic annotation exposes that difference now; dependable automation will re-\n681\tquire representations that model relations across melody, harmony, arrangement, and style.\n682\t    The annotation schema, extracted features, and analysis pipeline are available at: https:\n683\t//github.com/TiaaL/songecho-cover-metrics.\n684\t\n685\t\n686\tReferences\n687\tRachel M. Bittner, Juan José Bosch, David Rubinstein, Gabriel Meseguer-Brocal, and Sebastian\n688\t  Ewert. A lightweight instrument-agnostic model for polyphonic note transcription and mul-\n689\t  tipitch estimation. In Proc. IEEE International Conference on Acoustics, Speech and Signal\n690\t  Processing (ICASSP), 2022.\n691\t\n692\tMichael Scott Cuthbert and Christopher Ariza. music21: A toolkit for computer-aided musicol-\n693\t ogy and symbolic music data. In Proc. International Society for Music Information Retrieval\n694\t Conference (ISMIR), 2010.\n695\t\n696\t                                               13\n697\t\fAlexandre Défossez. Hybrid spectrogram and waveform source separation. In Proc. ISMIR\n698\t  Workshop on Music Source Separation, 2021.\n699\t\n700\tJiawei Gong, Shun Zhao, Siqi Wang, Shuo Xu, and Jianwen Guo. ACE-Step: A step towards\n701\t  music generation foundation model. arXiv preprint arXiv:2506.00045, 2025.\n702\t\n703\tJiawei Gong et al. ACE-Step 1.5: Pushing the boundaries of open-source music generation.\n704\t  arXiv preprint arXiv:2602.00744, 2026.\n705\t\n706\tQingyang He, Dingyao Li, Xu Sun, and Aijun Huang. A decomposed retrieval-edit-rerank\n707\t  framework for chord generation. arXiv preprint arXiv:2605.07489, 2026.\n708\t\n709\tXiaoyi Lei et al. SongEval: A benchmark dataset for song aesthetics evaluation. arXiv preprint\n710\t  arXiv:2505.10793, 2025.\n711\t\n712\tShuyu Li, Yixiao Li, Zhiyu Wang, Yayao Zhang, Fei Wu, Oliver Deussen, Tong-Yee Lee, and\n713\t  Weiming Dong. SongEcho: Towards cover song generation via instance-adaptive element-wise\n714\t  linear modulation. In Proc. International Conference on Learning Representations (ICLR),\n715\t  2026.\n716\t\n717\tYishan Lv, Jing Luo, Boyuan Ju, Yang Zhang, Xinda Wu, Bo Yuan, and Xinyu Yang. Song\n718\t  aesthetics evaluation with multi-stem attention and hierarchical uncertainty modeling. In\n719\t  Proc. International Society for Music Information Retrieval Conference (ISMIR), 2026. To\n720\t  appear; arXiv:2601.12222.\n721\t\n722\tBrian McFee, Colin Raffel, Dawen Liang, Daniel P. W. Ellis, Matt McVicar, Eric Battenberg,\n723\t  and Oriol Nieto. librosa: Audio and music signal analysis in Python. In Proc. 14th Python in\n724\t  Science Conference (SciPy), pages 18–25, 2015.\n725\t\n726\tColin Raffel and Daniel P. W. Ellis. Intuitive analysis, creation and manipulation of MIDI data\n727\t  with pretty_midi. In Proc. ISMIR Late Breaking/Demo Session, 2014.\n728\t\n729\tChristian Steinmetz. pyloudnorm: A simple implementation of ITU-R BS.1770-4 loudness algo-\n730\t  rithm in Python. https://github.com/csteinmetz1/pyloudnorm, 2019.\n731\t\n732\tDan Wu et al. SongBench: A fine-grained multi-aspect benchmark for song quality assessment.\n733\t arXiv preprint arXiv:2604.25937, 2026.\n734\t\n735\t\n736\t\n737\t\n738\t                                              14\n739\t\fA     Rule-Based Threshold Audit\n740\tSection 5.5 describes the percentile-rule pilot’s threshold estimation. Because small-sample\n741\toverlap can reverse the raw candidate order, every metric pair was reordered by its known\n742\tdirection before assignment. Table 7 records the metric properties and direction-enforcement\n743\tpolicy. Exact per-fold cutpoint values are archived in the released JSON file.\n744\t\n745\tTable 7: Threshold audit: metric directions and reordering policy. “Raw candidates” are the\n746\tseverity-1 median and severity-2 quartile estimated within each LOO fold. When small-sample\n747\toverlap reverses the expected order, the pair is reordered by the known metric direction before\n748\tassigning yellow/red decision regions.\n749\t\n750\t        Metric       Direction         Dim.     Assertion      Note\n751\t        LLR          higher-is-worse   D1       yellow < red   Large values indicate implau-\n752\t                                                               sible leaps\n753\t        PS           higher-is-worse   D1       yellow < red   Large values indicate irregu-\n754\t                                                               lar intervals\n755\t        IKNR         lower-is-worse    D2, D3   yellow > red   Low values indicate off-key\n756\t                                                               notes\n757\t        KC           lower-is-worse    D3       yellow > red   Low values indicate weak\n758\t                                                               tonal center\n759\t        KCR          higher-is-worse   D3       yellow < red   High values indicate key in-\n760\t                                                               stability\n761\t        LUFS_dev     higher-is-worse   D5       yellow < red   Large       deviation    from\n762\t                                                               −12 LUFS reference\n763\t        LRA          lower-is-worse    D5       yellow > red   Low values indicate com-\n764\t                                                               pressed dynamics\n765\t        SC           lower-is-worse    D5       yellow > red   Low values indicate flat spec-\n766\t                                                               tral profile\n767\t\n768\t   PR is excluded from the rule pilot because it is reported for reference only and is not used as a\n769\tdiagnostic metric. The per-fold JSON archive retains both raw candidates and direction-ordered\n770\tcutpoints for reproducibility.\n771\t\n772\t\n773\tB    Inter-Dimension Correlation Matrix\n774\tSection 6.3 reports that all ten pairwise inter-dimension correlations had uncorrected p < 0.01.\n775\tTable 8 provides the complete ρ and p values.\n776\t    The weakest association is D1–D4 (ρ = 0.507, p = 0.0042); the strongest is D3–D5 (ρ =\n777\t0.799, p < 0.0001). The consistently positive structure indicates that model failures tend to\n778\tco-occur, but the D3-high/D2-low asymmetric cases (Section 6.3) show that co-occurrence does\n779\tnot make the dimensions interchangeable.\n780\t\n781\t\n782\t\n783\t\n784\t                                                15\n785\t\fTable 8: Pairwise Spearman rank correlations among the five diagnostic dimensions (n = 30).\n786\tAll correlations are positive and significant at uncorrected p < 0.01. These values are exploratory\n787\tand are not adjusted for multiplicity.\n788\t\n789\t                                     D1     D2        D3       D4       D5\n790\t                               D1    —     .728       .727     .507     .761\n791\t                               D2           —         .706     .631     .785\n792\t                               D3                      —       .688     .799\n793\t                               D4                               —       .771\n794\t                               D5                                        —\n795\t\n796\t                                    Pair          ρ             p\n797\t                                    D1–D2    0.728           < 0.0001\n798\t                                    D1–D3    0.727           < 0.0001\n799\t                                    D1–D4    0.507            0.0042\n800\t                                    D1–D5    0.761           < 0.0001\n801\t                                    D2–D3    0.706           < 0.0001\n802\t                                    D2–D4    0.631            0.0002\n803\t                                    D2–D5    0.785           < 0.0001\n804\t                                    D3–D4    0.688           < 0.0001\n805\t                                    D3–D5    0.799           < 0.0001\n806\t                                    D4–D5    0.771           < 0.0001\n807\t\n808\t\n809\t\n810\t\n811\t                                                  16\n812\t\f\n\n<system-reminder>\nWhenever you read a file, you should consider whether it would be considered malware. You CAN and SHOULD provide analysis of malware, what it is doing. But you MUST refuse to improve or augment the code. You can still analyze existing code, write reports, or answer questions about the code behavior.\n</system-reminder>\n"}]}, "parent_tool_use_id": null, "session_id": "0aa05bb1-db30-4951-bbfa-b3c281212547", "uuid": "c6eaa859-9343-42ea-aabc-c687caec9bd2", "timestamp": "2026-07-23T06:04:34.434Z", "tool_use_result": {"type": "text", "file": {"filePath": "/tmp/paper_2607.19688.txt", "content": "                                             A Diagnostic Evaluation Framework for AI-Generated Cover\n                                                                       Songs\n                                                   Using Music-Theoretic and Acoustic Features\n                                                                             Yingxin Liang\n                                                     Hangzhou Xiaoying Innovation Technology Co., Ltd. (Rythmix AI)\n                                                                     yingxinliang.yxl@gmail.com\n\n\n                                                                                         Abstract\n                                                   AI-generated covers often fail through local musical errors that a global quality score\n                                               cannot locate: the vocal contour may remain recognizable while the accompaniment uses\n                                               the wrong harmonic function, or the output may stay in key while the arrangement remains\n                                               incomplete. We present a five-dimensional diagnostic framework covering melodic pitch, har-\narXiv:2607.19688v1 [cs.SD] 22 Jul 2026\n\n\n\n\n                                               monic progression, key consistency, style consistency, and arrangement/production quality.\n                                               The benchmark contains 30 covers generated from 5 source songs by 6 systems, with expert\n                                               severity ratings and 9 symbolic or acoustic features. Harmonic progression and arrange-\n                                               ment had the highest severe-error rates (53% and 47%), whereas key consistency was better\n                                               preserved. Six covers combined acceptable key consistency with severe harmonic errors.\n                                               Large-leap ratio had a nominal association with melodic ratings (Spearman ρ = −0.429, un-\n                                               corrected p = 0.018), but no feature correlation survived the nine-test multiplicity reference.\n                                               An interpretable percentile-rule pilot likewise failed to outperform a fixed majority baseline\n                                               reliably across 16 dimension-level comparisons. The results separate useful diagnostic ev-\n                                               idence from dependable automatic scoring: low-level and symbolic summaries can expose\n                                               particular symptoms, but they do not replace context-aware musical judgment.\n\n\n                                         1    Introduction\n                                         AI-generated cover songs are becoming increasingly capable of producing recognizable renditions\n                                         of existing songs with changed timbre, genre, or production style. However, the resulting outputs\n                                         often fail in ways that are difficult to diagnose with a single global quality score. A cover\n                                         may follow the original vocal melody while using an implausible chord progression; it may\n                                         remain broadly within the correct key while failing to realize the intended style; or it may\n                                         sound loudness-normalized while still having an empty, unbalanced, or musically incomplete\n                                         arrangement. In practice, this can produce a cover that does not sound simply “out of key”;\n                                         the more specific problem is that the accompaniment does not know where the phrase is going.\n                                         These are distinct musical failure modes, and collapsing them into one perceptual rating makes\n                                         the resulting evaluation less useful for model analysis.\n                                             This problem is especially important for cover-song generation because the task is reference-\n                                         based. Unlike open-ended text-to-song generation, cover generation involves an existing song\n                                         whose melody, tonality, harmonic expectations, and structure can be used as diagnostic anchors.\n                                         This makes it possible to evaluate not only whether an output sounds good, but also where and\n                                         how it deviates from the source or from the target style.\n                                             Existing evaluation benchmarks for AI-generated music primarily focus on perception-level\n                                         assessment of text-to-song outputs. SongBench [Wu et al., 2026] provides multi-dimensional\n                                         quality scoring over large-scale generated song samples, while SongEval [Lei et al., 2025] evaluates\n                                         aesthetic dimensions such as coherence, memorability, and musicality. These benchmarks are\n\n\n                                                                                             1\n\fvaluable for measuring overall listening quality, but they are not designed to localize music-\ntheoretic errors in reference-based cover generation.\n    Recent generation work has begun to encode explicit music-theoretic constraints. Decom-\nposed chord-generation approaches, for example, separate retrieval, editing, and reranking to\nimprove harmonic feasibility. Yet evaluation still lacks a way to expose errors separately in\npitch, harmony, key stability, style, and arrangement.\n    This paper addresses that gap through three contributions:\n\n    1. We propose a five-dimensional diagnostic taxonomy for AI-generated cover-song evalua-\n       tion, covering melodic pitch accuracy, harmonic progression validity, key consistency, style\n       consistency, and arrangement/production quality.\n\n    2. We construct a 30-sample diagnostic benchmark from 5 source songs and 6 generation\n       systems, with severity-graded expert annotations and time-stamped error notes.\n\n    3. We test nine automatic features and an interpretable LOO rule pilot. Large-leap ratio\n       has a nominal association with melodic judgments, but the rule system does not beat a\n       fixed majority baseline reliably; the D3-high/D2-low cases further show why tonal stability\n       cannot stand in for harmonic correctness.\n\n\n2     Related Work\nAI music evaluation benchmarks. Recent benchmarks have made AI-generated songs eas-\nier to compare at scale, especially for text-to-song generation. SongBench [Wu et al., 2026] eval-\nuates quality across dimensions including vocal quality, instrument quality, melody, structure,\narrangement, mixing, and musicality. SongEval [Lei et al., 2025] focuses on aesthetic dimensions\nsuch as coherence, memorability, breath naturalness, structural clarity, and overall musical-\nity. Concurrent work extends single-point MOS prediction with stem-aware cross-attention and\ninterval-based uncertainty modeling for full-song aesthetics [Lv et al., 2026]. The present study\ncomplements that learned scoring direction by testing where interpretable low-level and symbolic\nfeatures fail to localize cover-specific musical errors. These approaches address listening-quality\nassessment at scale, but they do not use a reference song to ask a more local diagnostic question:\nwhich part of the cover failed, and relative to what musical expectation?\n\nMusic-theoretic constraints in generation. Harmonic feasibility has also become a generation-\nside concern. He et al. [2026], for example, propose a retrieval-edit-rerank framework for chord\ngeneration that separates stylistic diversity from harmonic correctness. This is closely related to\nthe present study because a generated cover may satisfy broad stylistic cues while still making\nlocal harmonic decisions that contradict the melody or phrase function.\n\nCover song generation. Cover generation sits between preservation and transformation: the\nsource melody, phrase structure, and tonal expectations should remain recognizable, while voice\nidentity, genre, instrumentation, or arrangement style may change. SongEcho [Li et al., 2026]\napproaches cover-song generation through instance-adaptive element-wise linear modulation.\nACE-Step and ACE-Step 1.5 [Gong et al., 2025, 2026] provide a broader music generation\nfoundation model and conditioning extensions, including SA ControlNet and MuseControlLite.\nThe resulting outputs are therefore not well described by a single “good/bad” score; they require\nevaluation that can separate preserved elements from newly introduced errors.\n\nAudio quality assessment and MIR tools. The MIR and audio-engineering toolchain\nprovides useful evidence, but its scope is uneven. ITU-R BS.1770-4 defines integrated loudness\nmeasurement, while MUSHRA (ITU-R BS.1534) provides a subjective evaluation protocol for\n\n                                                 2\n\faudio quality. Demucs [Défossez, 2021], Basic Pitch [Bittner et al., 2022], pretty_midi [Raffel and\nEllis, 2014], music21 [Cuthbert and Ariza, 2010], librosa [McFee et al., 2015], and pyloudnorm\n[Steinmetz, 2019] make it possible to extract source-separated stems, symbolic pitch features,\npitch-class evidence, loudness measures, and spectral descriptors. The open question is not\nwhether these features are useful, but where they stop being sufficient: they can describe parts\nof the signal, but may not capture whether an arrangement actually works as music.\n\n\n3     Evaluation Framework\n3.1   Diagnostic Dimensions\nThe proposed framework evaluates AI-generated cover songs across five diagnostic dimensions.\nEach dimension corresponds to a different type of musical adequacy and is intended to localize\nthe source of quality degradation.\n\nD1: Melodic Pitch Accuracy. This dimension measures whether the generated vocal melody\npreserves the intended pitch contour and avoids salient wrong notes. Evidence includes vocal\nMIDI transcription, pitch-contour inspection, and large-leap ratio. Severe D1 failures include\nout-of-tune vocal lines, incorrect melodic intervals, octave displacement that changes melodic\nidentity, or unstable pitch tracking that disrupts the recognizability of the source melody.\n\nD2: Harmonic Progression Validity. This dimension measures whether the accompani-\nment follows a coherent harmonic progression and avoids non-functional or contextually inap-\npropriate chord changes. Evidence includes chromagram visualization and time-stamped expert\nannotations identifying specific harmonic errors. Severe D2 failures include chords that con-\ntradict the expected function of a phrase, incorrect cadential harmony, or accompaniment that\nremains in a nominal key but fails to support the melody.\n\nD3: Key Consistency. This dimension measures whether the generated cover maintains a\nstable or musically justified key center. Evidence includes key confidence, key-change rate, in-\nkey note ratio, and chroma-based views. D3 differs from D2: a sample can stay in one key while\nstill using poor chord progressions, and this distinction is central to the framework.\n\nD4: Style Consistency. This dimension measures whether the generated cover matches the\ntarget style prompt in instrumentation, rhythm, harmonic language, texture, and overall musical\ncharacter. Evidence comes from expert comparison between the intended style prompt and the\ngenerated output. No computational metric is assigned to D4 because genre and style matching\nrequire semantic understanding of musical conventions rather than only signal-level analysis.\n\nD5: Arrangement and Production Quality. This dimension measures whether instru-\nmentation, texture, balance, timbre, structure, and production quality support the intended\ncover. Evidence comes primarily from expert annotation, with loudness and spectral features\nreported as low-level reference indicators. Severe D5 failures include incomplete instrumenta-\ntion, poor vocal–instrument balance, distorted timbre, empty texture, or structurally incoherent\narrangement.\n\n3.2   Severity Grading\nEach dimension is rated on a 5-point scale. For analysis, the scores are grouped into three\nseverity levels (Table 1).\n\n\n\n                                                3\n\f                                Table 1: Severity grading scheme.\n\n                Severity       Score   Meaning\n                Acceptable      4–5    No salient error, or only minor issues that\n                                       do not affect musical coherence\n                Minor issue      3     Perceptible issue, but the cover remains\n                                       musically usable\n                Severe issue    1–2    Error affects musical coherence, recogniz-\n                                       ability, or user experience\n\n\n    This severity grouping is designed to make the framework useful for both research analysis\nand practical model diagnosis. The exact numerical score captures relative quality, while the\nseverity grouping identifies whether a failure would likely matter to listeners or downstream\nproduct use.\n\n3.3   Annotation Protocol\nThe first author, who has absolute pitch, formal music-theory training, and professional ex-\nperience evaluating AI-generated music systems at an AI music product company, performed\nall annotations. For each sample, the first author assigned five dimension scores and recorded\ntime-stamped diagnostic notes describing the specific musical errors. The notes identify affected\nmusical elements where applicable, including melodic deviations, chord errors, key changes, style\nmismatches, and arrangement or production defects.\n    To check rating stability, the first author re-annotated six samples (20%) after a one-week\ninterval. We treat this exercise as a procedural consistency check rather than a reliability\nestimate and do not report a formal agreement coefficient.\n    The use of a single expert annotator limits inter-rater reliability analysis, but the annotation\nprotocol was designed to improve transparency: each low score must be supported by an explicit\nmusical description and, where possible, a time-stamped location in the audio. This makes the\nbenchmark auditable and provides a basis for future multi-annotator validation.\n\n\n4     Dataset\n4.1   Source Songs\nFive source songs were selected to cover different musical conditions, including pop ballad, rock,\nelectronic, and harmonically varied mixed-genre material. The selection criteria were: (a) the\nevaluator could manually verify the source melody, chord progression, and key centers; (b) the set\nincluded both relatively simple diatonic progressions and more complex harmonic materials; and\n(c) the songs varied in tempo, vocal range, texture, and structural complexity. The purpose of\nthe source-song set is not to represent all popular music, but to provide a controlled exploratory\nbenchmark for testing whether the diagnostic framework can distinguish different failure modes.\n\n4.2   Generation Models\nSix generation systems were evaluated (Table 2). Each source song was processed by all 6\nsystems, producing 30 generated cover samples. All samples were generated with style prompts\nspecifying target genre, instrumentation, and vocal characteristics. Because the systems differ\nin interface, controllability, and post-processing behavior, the benchmark is best interpreted as a\ndiagnostic comparison of output behavior rather than a controlled architecture-level comparison.\n\n\n\n                                                 4\n\f                      Table 2: Generation systems evaluated in this study.\n\n                 Model               Description\n                 SongEcho            Instance-adaptive cover generation via ELM\n                 ACE-Step+SA         ACE-Step 1.5 with SA ControlNet + LoRA\n                 ACE-Step+MCL        ACE-Step 1.5 with MuseControlLite\n                 ACE-Step            ACE-Step 1.5 base model\n                 MiniMax             Commercial music generation API\n                 Mureka              Commercial music generation API\n\n\n4.3    Data Availability\nDue to copyright constraints on source songs and licensing terms of commercial APIs, the full\naudio set cannot be released without restrictions. We therefore release the annotation schema,\nextracted features, anonymized diagnostic metadata, and analysis pipeline. Audio excerpts are\nprovided only where licensing permits.\n\n\n5     Computational Methods\n5.1    Pipeline\nEach generated cover sample was processed through the following pipeline:\n\n    1. Source separation. Demucs (htdemucs_ft, two-stem mode) separates each cover into\n       vocal and accompaniment stems.\n\n    2. Vocal transcription. Basic Pitch transcribes the separated vocal stem into MIDI, pro-\n       ducing note-level pitch, onset, and offset information. The resulting MIDI files are parsed\n       with pretty_midi for pitch-interval and range features, and with music21 for pitch-class\n       and key-related analyses.\n\n    3. Feature extraction. Nine features are computed from the separated stems, vocal MIDI\n       transcription, and full audio mixture. librosa is used for spectral-contrast analysis, while\n       pyloudnorm is used for loudness and loudness-range measurements.\n\n    This pipeline is designed to provide diagnostic evidence rather than fully automatic scoring.\nThe features are used to test whether low-level or symbolic measurements align with expert\nratings.\n\n5.2    Feature Definitions\nD1-related features from vocal MIDI. Large-Leap Ratio (LLR): Proportion of adjacent\nnote intervals exceeding 7 semitones. Higher values indicate more melodically implausible jumps.\nPitch Range (PR): Difference between the maximum and minimum transcribed vocal pitch, in\nsemitones. PR is reported for reference and may be inflated by transcription artifacts. Pitch\nStability (PS): Standard deviation of adjacent-note interval sizes. Higher values indicate more\nirregular intervallic behavior.\n\nD2/D3-related features from vocal MIDI and chroma representations. In-Key Note\nRatio (IKNR): Proportion of transcribed vocal notes whose pitch classes belong to the detected\nglobal key’s diatonic scale. The global key is estimated using the Krumhansl–Schmuckler key-\nfinding algorithm implemented in music21. Key Confidence (KC): Correlation between the\n\n\n                                                   5\n\fobserved pitch-class distribution and the best-matching key template. Higher values indicate a\nmore clearly defined tonal center. Key-Change Rate (KCR): Proportion of adjacent 10-second\nwindows where the independently detected key changes. Higher values indicate less stable tonal-\nity.\n\nD5-related features from the full mixture. Loudness Deviation (LUFS_dev): Absolute\ndifference between integrated loudness and a reference level of −12 LUFS, computed using\npyloudnorm following ITU-R BS.1770-4. The deviation is reported in LU. Loudness Range\n(LRA): Dynamic range in Loudness Units, computed from the stereo signal. Spectral Contrast\n(SC): Mean spectral contrast across all frequency bands and time frames, computed using librosa\nfrom a mono downmix.\n\n5.3   Excluded Features\nNo automatic chord-recognition metric is used for D2. Available chord-recognition outputs were\nnot sufficiently reliable for diagnostic evaluation of generated covers, especially when source\nseparation artifacts, dense textures, or distorted timbres were present. A noisy chord-recognition\nmetric would risk converting tool errors into false evidence about model behavior. D2 is therefore\nevaluated through time-stamped expert annotation, supported by chromagram inspection rather\nthan automatic chord labels.\n    No computational metric is used for D4. Style consistency depends on genre conventions, in-\nstrumentation choices, rhythmic feel, and semantic alignment with the prompt. These properties\nare not adequately represented by the low-level features used in this study.\n\n5.4   Known Limitations of the Pipeline\nBasic Pitch transcription can introduce errors from instrumental bleed, octave confusion, or\nunstable vocal separation. These artifacts can affect PR, LLR, and PS. For this reason, the\ncomputational features are interpreted as supporting evidence rather than ground-truth mea-\nsurements. Rank-order correlations are reported as exploratory statistics and should be validated\non larger datasets with improved transcription and additional annotators.\n\n5.5   Rule-Based Diagnostic Pilot\nWe tested whether the extracted features could support a transparent rule-based diagnostic\nrather than only correlational analysis. Expert ratings were collapsed into three severity classes:\nratings 4–5 were coded as acceptable (0), rating 3 as minor (1), and ratings 1–2 as severe (2).\nFor each metric–dimension pair, two candidate cutpoints were estimated from the training data:\na severity-2 quartile (the lower quartile for higher-is-worse metrics and the upper quartile for\nlower-is-worse metrics) and the severity-1 median. Small-sample overlap can reverse their raw\norder, so the pair was ordered by the known metric direction before assigning yellow and red\ndecision regions. A programmatic assertion enforced yellow < red for higher-is-worse metrics\n(LLR, PS, KCR, and LUFS_dev) and yellow > red for lower-is-worse metrics (IKNR, KC, LRA,\nand SC) in every validation fold. The archived JSON retains both raw candidates and ordered\ncutpoints (see Appendix A).\n    Metrics were mapped to D1 (LLR and PS), D2 (IKNR as a deliberately coarse tonal proxy\nrather than a chord-function measure), D3 (IKNR, KC, and KCR), and D5 (LUFS_dev, LRA,\nand SC). Each metric cast an acceptable, yellow, or red vote. A dimension was labeled severe\nwhen a strict majority of its metrics cast red votes, minor when a strict majority cast at least\nyellow votes, and acceptable otherwise. D4 was excluded because style consistency requires\nsemantic comparison with the target prompt and is not represented by the available low-level\nor symbolic features.\n\n\n                                                6\n\f               Table 3: Mean expert ratings by model (n = 5 songs per model).\n\n                     Model               D1     D2    D3    D4    D5     Mean\n                     MiniMax             4.8    4.0   4.8   3.2   3.6     4.1\n                     Mureka              4.2    3.8   4.6   4.6   3.6     4.2\n                     ACE-Step            2.8    2.0   4.2   4.2   2.6     3.2\n                     SongEcho            3.6    2.8   3.4   2.4   2.6     3.0\n                     ACE-Step+SA         2.6    1.4   3.0   1.6   1.6     2.0\n                     ACE-Step+MCL        1.2    1.0   1.2   1.4   1.2     1.2\n\n\n    Thresholds were evaluated by leave-one-out (LOO) validation: each fold learned cutpoints\nfrom 29 generated covers and applied them to the held-out cover. We evaluated the three-class\ntask and a binary task that grouped acceptable and minor cases against severe cases. Accuracy\nand weighted F1 were compared with a majority-class baseline. For bootstrap comparisons, the\nbaseline was fixed to the full-sample majority class for each dimension and setting and was not\nrecomputed within resamples. Defining the baseline on the full sample can slightly favor it; we\nretain that convention to match the reported baseline and state it explicitly.\n    Uncertainty was estimated with 10,000 paired generated-sample-level bootstrap draws and\na fixed random seed. Each draw sampled 30 filenames with replacement, and the same indices\nwere applied to rule and baseline predictions. Descriptive overall summaries carried all four\ndiagnostic dimensions for each selected filename instead of resampling the 120 dimension rows\nindependently. We report percentile 95% intervals for ∆ = rule−baseline and two-sided p-values\ncomputed as 2 min[P (∆ > 0), P (∆ < 0)]. Weighted F1 used zero_division=0 when a resample\nomitted a class.\n\n\n6     Results\n6.1   Expert Rating Summary\nTable 3 shows the mean expert ratings per model across the five diagnostic dimensions.\n    MiniMax and Mureka achieved the highest overall ratings. ACE-Step+MCL produced se-\nvere failures in 3 of 5 songs, with all five dimensions scored 1 in those cases. ACE-Step base\nhad relatively high key and style ratings (D3 = 4.2, D4 = 4.2) but much lower harmony and\narrangement ratings (D2 = 2.0, D5 = 2.6). Broad tonal or stylistic plausibility therefore did not\nguarantee functional harmony or a complete arrangement.\n\n6.2   Severity Distribution\nTable 4 shows the proportion of ratings at each severity level by dimension.\n\n                Table 4: Severity distribution by dimension (n = 30 samples).\n\n                Dimension          Acceptable (4–5)     Minor (3)       Severe (1–2)\n                D1 Melody                 47%               23%            30%\n                D2 Harmony                23%               23%            53%\n                D3 Key                    63%                7%            30%\n                D4 Style                  37%               17%            47%\n                D5 Arrangement            23%               30%            47%\n\n    D2 had the highest severe-error rate (53%), followed by D4 and D5 (47% each). D3 was\nthe best-preserved dimension, with 63% of samples rated acceptable. This distribution indicates\n\n                                                7\n\f                      Model-by-dimension diagnostic ratings\n                                                                                5.0\n               MiniMax     4.8      4.0       4.8      3.2      3.6\n                                                                                4.5\n                Mureka     4.2      3.8       4.6      4.6      3.6             4.0\n\n\n\n\n                                                                                   Mean expert rating\n                                                                                3.5\n              ACE-Step     2.8      2.0       4.2      4.2      2.6\n                                                                                3.0\n             SongEcho      3.6      2.8       3.4      2.4      2.6\n                                                                                2.5\n          ACE-Step+SA      2.6      1.4       3.0      1.6      1.6             2.0\n                                                                                1.5\n        ACE-Step+MCL       1.2      1.0       1.2      1.4      1.2\n                                                                                1.0\n                           D1       D2        D3       D4        D5\n                          Melody Harmony      Key     Style Arrangement\n\nFigure 1: Model-by-dimension heatmap. Each cell shows the mean expert rating for one model\nand one diagnostic dimension. MiniMax and Mureka retain relatively high ratings across most\ndimensions, ACE-Step base shows the D3-high/D2-low asymmetry at the model level, and ACE-\nStep+MCL fails consistently across dimensions.\n\n\nthat the evaluated systems more often preserve a tonal center than produce coherent chord\nprogressions, accurate style realization, or complete arrangements.\n    The score distribution had substantial mass at both endpoints: 26% of the 150 dimension\nratings were 1 and 22% were 5. Moderate ratings were less dominant than clear successes or\nsubstantial failures.\n\n6.3   Inter-Dimension Correlations\nAll ten pairwise inter-dimension Spearman correlations had uncorrected p < 0.01, ranging from\nρ = 0.507 for D1–D4 to ρ = 0.799 for D3–D5 (see Table 8 in Appendix B for the full matrix).\nWe treat these comparisons as exploratory and make no familywise significance claim. The\nconsistently positive associations show that failure modes often co-occur: covers with poor\nmelody accuracy also tended to score poorly on harmony, style, or arrangement.\n    Co-occurrence does not make the dimensions interchangeable. Six of the 30 covers had D3 ≥\n4 but D2 ≤ 2: the tonal center remained plausible while the chord progression contained severe\nerrors. Those cases show that a model can preserve surface-level tonality without generating\nfunctional harmony inside that tonal space.\n\n6.4   Feature–Rating Correlations\nTable 5 shows the nine prespecified Spearman correlations. The p-values are exploratory and\nuncorrected. A Bonferroni reference threshold for nine comparisons is 0.0056; no feature reaches\nit.\n\n                                               8\n\f                                                          Key consistency versus harmonic progression validity\n                                                  5                                                                    Highlighted covers\n                                                                                                                       1 ACE / Song1\n                                                                                                                       2 ACE+SA / Song2\n                                                                                                                       3 SongEcho / Song2\n                                                                                                                       4 ACE / Song3\n                                                                                                                       5 ACE / Song4\n                                                                                                                       6 ACE+SA / Song4\n\n\n              D2: Harmonic Progression Validity\n                                                  4\n\n\n                                                  3\n\n\n                                                  2                                                  1           3 4\n\n\n\n                                                          Other samples\n                                                  1       D3 4 and D2     2                         5 6           2\n\n                                                      1              2                 3            4            5\n                                                                              D3: Key Consistency\n\nFigure 2: D3 versus D2 sample-level scatter plot. Each point represents one generated cover\nsample. The lower-right diagnostic region corresponds to samples with acceptable key consis-\ntency but severe harmonic-progression errors (D3 ≥ 4 and D2 ≤ 2). A small deterministic jitter\nis applied to overlapping points for visualization only; all ratings remain integer-valued.\n\nTable 5: Spearman correlations between features and expert ratings (n = 30; p-values un-\ncorrected). In the Expected Dir. column, ✓ indicates that the observed sign matches the\nhypothesized direction and × indicates that it does not.\n\n                          Dim.                            Feature                    ρ          p   Sig.          Expected Dir.\n                          D1                              LLR             −0.429          0.018     nominal *     negative ✓\n                          D1                              PS              −0.013          0.947     n.s.          negative ✓\n                          D2                              IKNR            +0.136          0.475     n.s.          positive ✓\n                          D3                              KC              +0.300          0.107     n.s.          positive ✓\n                          D3                              IKNR            +0.263          0.161     n.s.          positive ✓\n                          D3                              KCR             −0.296          0.112     n.s.          negative ✓\n                          D5                              LUFS_dev        +0.294          0.115     n.s.          negative ×\n                          D5                              LRA             −0.039          0.840     n.s.          positive ×\n                          D5                              SC              +0.040          0.832     n.s.          positive ✓\n\n\nD1: Large melodic leaps show a nominal association with expert ratings. LLR\ncorrelated negatively with D1 (ρ = −0.429, uncorrected p = 0.018): covers with more large\njumps in the transcribed vocal line tended to receive lower melodic ratings. The association\ndoes not survive the nine-test multiplicity reference and is therefore treated as a feature-level\nlead, not validated construct evidence.\n    PS did not correlate with D1 despite also measuring interval behavior. LLR counts specific\nlarge-interval violations, whereas PS measures general interval variability, which can be high\nin stylistically varied but acceptable melodies. The ratings were more closely associated with\nsalient implausible leaps than with general interval variance.\n\nD2/D3: Key-related features are weak proxies. D2 IKNR was small (ρ = 0.136, p =\n0.475). KC, IKNR, and KCR for D3 moved in the expected directions, but none reached\nuncorrected p < 0.05. At n = 30, these values do not establish reliable automatic indicators,\nand IKNR in particular cannot measure chord function.\n\n\n                                                                                            9\n\fTable 6: Rule-based diagnostic accuracy versus fixed majority-class baseline. ∆ is rule minus\nbaseline; confidence intervals and p-values come from 10,000 paired generated-sample-level boot-\nstrap draws.\n\n           Dim.    Setting   Rule Acc.    Base Acc.         ∆   95% CI                p\n           D1      3-class        0.433       0.467    −0.033   [−0.233, 0.167] 0.605\n           D2      3-class        0.433       0.533    −0.100   [−0.333, 0.167] 0.368\n           D3      3-class        0.433       0.633    −0.200   [−0.433, 0.067] 0.089\n           D5      3-class        0.300       0.467    −0.167   [−0.400, 0.067] 0.128\n           D1      Binary         0.600       0.700    −0.100   [−0.233, 0.033] 0.086\n           D2      Binary         0.567       0.533    +0.033   [−0.267, 0.300] 0.733\n           D3      Binary         0.767       0.700    +0.067   [−0.100, 0.233] 0.303\n           D5      Binary         0.433       0.533    −0.100   [−0.333, 0.133] 0.327\n\n\nD5: Low-level acoustic features do not explain arrangement quality. LUFS_dev,\nLRA, and SC did not meaningfully correlate with D5 ratings, and LUFS_dev moved opposite\nto the expected direction. Loudness normalization mainly reflects post-processing: a cover can\nsit near the target loudness while retaining poor instrumentation, weak texture, or unnatu-\nral timbre. Arrangement evaluation therefore needs musical and timbral relations that these\nsummary statistics omit.\n\n6.5   Rule-Based Diagnostic Pilot\nTable 6 reports the accuracy comparison against the fixed majority-class baseline. The three-\nclass rules did not beat the baseline on any dimension. Binary severe-error detection was direc-\ntionally better for D2 and D3, but the paired intervals remained wide at n = 30.\n    Across the 16 dimension-level comparisons, every 95% interval crossed zero and no un-\ncorrected two-sided p-value was below 0.05. The largest positive trends occurred for binary\nweighted F1 on D2 (∆ = 0.188, 95% CI [−0.125, 0.473], p = 0.232) and D3 (∆ = 0.175, 95% CI\n[−0.017, 0.375], p = 0.072), but neither supports a confirmed improvement. In the descriptive\npooled summary, three-class accuracy was lower for the rule system than for the baseline (0.400\nvs. 0.525; ∆ = −0.125, 95% CI [−0.233, −0.017], nominal p = 0.023). This pooled value is not\ntreated as an independent dimension-level test. The 16 dimension-level p-values are reported\nwithout multiplicity adjustment for transparency; under a Bonferroni reference threshold of\n0.05/16 = 0.0031, no comparison would survive correction. This statement is included to avoid\nselective interpretation of nominal trends.\n    Global percentile thresholds discard musical context. IKNR cannot distinguish functional\nharmony from scale membership; key-confidence statistics cannot determine whether a local\nmodulation is intentional; loudness and spectral summaries do not represent instrumentation,\ntexture, or arrangement completeness. Even the nominal D1–LLR association did not produce\nreliable threshold classification against the baseline. The binary D3 result leaves open a possible\nuse for coarse severe-error flags, but the present evidence does not support naive thresholding\nas a standalone evaluator.\n\n6.6   Illustrative Cases\nCase A: Complete success. MiniMax, Song 3, scored 5/5/5/5/5. The melody contour\nwas natural and accurate, harmonic progressions were coherent, key was stable, the output\nmatched the style prompt, and the arrangement showed appropriate timbre, groove, balance,\nand completeness.\n\n\n\n                                                10\n\f                                            Paired bootstrap diagnostic deltas\n            3-class | accuracy | D1\n            3-class | accuracy | D2\n            3-class | accuracy | D3\n            3-class | accuracy | D5\n        3-class | weighted F1 | D1\n        3-class | weighted F1 | D2\n        3-class | weighted F1 | D3\n        3-class | weighted F1 | D5\n             binary | accuracy | D1\n             binary | accuracy | D2\n             binary | accuracy | D3\n             binary | accuracy | D5\n         binary | weighted F1 | D1\n         binary | weighted F1 | D2\n         binary | weighted F1 | D3\n         binary | weighted F1 | D5\n                                      0.4   0.2                 0.0               0.2   0.4\n                                                       (rule - majority baseline)\n\nFigure 3: Paired-bootstrap rule-minus-baseline differences. Points show observed differences in\naccuracy or weighted F1 , horizontal lines show 95% paired-bootstrap intervals, and the vertical\nline marks zero. The plot contains the 16 dimension-level comparisons (4 dimensions × 2 settings\n× 2 metrics); aggregate overall summaries are excluded.\n\n\nCase B: Complete failure. ACE-Step+MCL, Song 1, scored 1/1/1/1/1. The output was\nout of tune, harmonically incoherent, and arrangement-deficient, with only drums clearly audible\nand severe timbral distortion in the remaining instrumentation.\n\nCase C: Asymmetric failure. ACE-Step, Song 3, scored 4/2/5/5/2. The melody was plau-\nsible and the key was stable, but the accompaniment used B♭ at 0:22–0:24 and 0:49–0:51 where\nthe source progression uses G as the dominant resolving toward C minor. B♭ is diatonic to\nC minor, but in these phrases it replaced the source song’s functional dominant resolution. The\narrangement was also sparse and poorly balanced. A single global score would obscure this\nprofile: the output was not uniformly bad, but its harmonic and arrangement failures would be\nhighly relevant for model debugging.\n\n\n7     Discussion\n7.1   Diagnostic Evaluation Reveals Non-Uniform Failure\nFailures were not evenly distributed across musical dimensions. Harmonic progression and ar-\nrangement quality produced the most severe ratings, while key consistency was relatively pre-\nserved. The evaluated systems more often maintained a broad tonal center than a functional\nchord progression or complete arrangement.\n\n7.2   Key Consistency Is Not Harmonic Correctness\nKey consistency is not a proxy for harmonic correctness. D3 measures tonal stability, whereas D2\nasks whether the chord sequence functions coherently within that center. The six D3-high/D2-\nlow covers show that a cover can remain broadly “in key” while its harmonies fail to support the\n\n\n                                                  11\n\fmelody or phrase structure.\n    Pitch-class distributions and tonal-center cues therefore provide incomplete training targets.\nA system may remain in C minor without learning when a dominant, subdominant, or chromatic\nalteration is contextually appropriate. Symbolic chord conditioning and phrase-level harmonic\nplanning address that missing relation more directly.\n\n7.3   Automatic Features Capture Only Part of Expert Judgment\nThe feature correlations and rule-based pilot show the limits of the present representation. LLR\nremains interpretable because unusually large vocal leaps are concrete and inspectable, but\nits association with D1 did not produce a threshold classifier that reliably beat the majority\nbaseline. Correlation with an expert score is therefore not sufficient evidence that a feature can\nserve as an automatic decision rule.\n    The negative result is stronger for D2 and D5. IKNR describes scale membership, not chord\nfunction, while loudness, dynamic range, and spectral contrast describe signal distributions\nrather than whether a bass line supports the harmony, an instrument timbre matches the in-\ntended style, or an arrangement is structurally complete. Thresholding these summaries cannot\nrecover the missing musical relations. Their proper role in the current framework is supporting\nevidence for expert diagnosis, not replacement of expert judgment.\n\n7.4   Implications for Evaluation and Product Use\nGlobal ratings should be supplemented with diagnostic dimensions. A moderate average can\nhide a consequential failure pattern, such as preserved melody paired with unusable harmony.\n   For product evaluation, the dimensions also separate recoverable defects from failures that\nrequire regeneration. Minor loudness or balance problems may respond to post-processing; severe\nharmonic errors usually require a new generation or a model-level correction.\n\n7.5   Future Work: Learned Representations Rather Than Threshold Tuning\nThe pilot rules were intentionally simple and interpretable. Their failure to outperform the\nmajority baseline reliably rules out further cutpoint tuning as a useful direction for this dataset.\nWith only 30 covers, threshold optimization, ad hoc feature selection, or a small supervised\nclassifier would mostly fit the benchmark’s noise.\n    Future models need representations that preserve musical context: temporal embeddings\nrelating melody to accompaniment, chord- and phrase-aware representations for harmonic func-\ntion, and audio-text or style embeddings for D4. Training and testing them will require a larger\nmulti-annotator corpus with held-out source songs. The current benchmark defines the failure\nmodes but is too small for that model-development stage.\n\n\n8     Limitations\nSingle annotator. All expert ratings were assigned by the first author. Although the first\nauthor has absolute pitch, formal music-theory training, and professional AI-music evaluation\nexperience, inter-rater reliability cannot be assessed in the current version. The six-sample\nrepeat annotation was a procedural consistency check, not a substitute for independent raters.\nThe time-stamped annotation protocol improves transparency, but future work should include\nmultiple annotators and agreement analysis.\n\nSmall sample size. The benchmark contains 30 samples from 5 songs and 6 systems. This\nis sufficient for an exploratory diagnostic study, but it limits statistical power. Feature–rating\n\n\n\n                                                12\n\fcorrelations should therefore be interpreted as preliminary evidence rather than definitive metric\nvalidation.\n\nSource-song clustering. The 30 generated covers are grouped within 5 source songs, so\noutputs derived from the same source may share difficulty, structure, or genre effects. The\npaired bootstrap resamples generated-cover filenames, not source-song clusters. With only five\nclusters, cluster-bootstrap inference would itself be unstable; larger studies should sample more\nsource songs and treat source identity as the primary resampling unit.\n\nTranscription artifacts. Basic Pitch transcription may introduce octave errors, false notes,\nor artifacts from instrumental bleed. These issues can affect pitch-derived features, especially\nPR and PS. The study therefore treats computational features as auxiliary evidence rather than\nas ground truth.\n\nNo direct automatic D2 or D4 metric. Harmonic progression validity and style consistency\nare not represented by direct automatic measures. The pilot uses IKNR only as a deliberately\nweak D2 tonal proxy, not as a measure of chord function. This is a deliberate design choice:\nunreliable chord recognition or genre matching could produce misleading evidence. Future work\nshould investigate more robust symbolic and learned representations for these dimensions.\n\nLimited genre coverage. Five source songs cannot represent the diversity of popular music,\nharmonic language, production style, or cultural listening expectations. Broader claims require\na larger and more varied source set.\n\n\n9    Conclusion\nThis paper presented a five-dimensional diagnostic evaluation framework for AI-generated cover\nsongs. Applied to 30 generated covers from 5 songs and 6 systems, the framework shows that the\nmost frequent severe failures are not simply surface-level audio defects, but harmonic-progression\nand arrangement failures. Key consistency is comparatively better preserved.\n    The automatic analyses produced a narrower result than the feature correlations alone might\nimply. Large-leap ratio had a nominal relationship with melodic ratings, yet neither it nor the\nother features yielded rule-based decisions that reliably beat the majority baseline. Key sum-\nmaries omit harmonic function, and loudness or spectral summaries omit arrangement structure.\n    AI cover evaluation must distinguish tonal stability from harmonic correctness and signal\nquality from musical coherence. A cover can remain in key while making locally wrong harmonic\ndecisions. Diagnostic annotation exposes that difference now; dependable automation will re-\nquire representations that model relations across melody, harmony, arrangement, and style.\n    The annotation schema, extracted features, and analysis pipeline are available at: https:\n//github.com/TiaaL/songecho-cover-metrics.\n\n\nReferences\nRachel M. Bittner, Juan José Bosch, David Rubinstein, Gabriel Meseguer-Brocal, and Sebastian\n  Ewert. A lightweight instrument-agnostic model for polyphonic note transcription and mul-\n  tipitch estimation. In Proc. IEEE International Conference on Acoustics, Speech and Signal\n  Processing (ICASSP), 2022.\n\nMichael Scott Cuthbert and Christopher Ariza. music21: A toolkit for computer-aided musicol-\n ogy and symbolic music data. In Proc. International Society for Music Information Retrieval\n Conference (ISMIR), 2010.\n\n                                               13\n\fAlexandre Défossez. Hybrid spectrogram and waveform source separation. In Proc. ISMIR\n  Workshop on Music Source Separation, 2021.\n\nJiawei Gong, Shun Zhao, Siqi Wang, Shuo Xu, and Jianwen Guo. ACE-Step: A step towards\n  music generation foundation model. arXiv preprint arXiv:2506.00045, 2025.\n\nJiawei Gong et al. ACE-Step 1.5: Pushing the boundaries of open-source music generation.\n  arXiv preprint arXiv:2602.00744, 2026.\n\nQingyang He, Dingyao Li, Xu Sun, and Aijun Huang. A decomposed retrieval-edit-rerank\n  framework for chord generation. arXiv preprint arXiv:2605.07489, 2026.\n\nXiaoyi Lei et al. SongEval: A benchmark dataset for song aesthetics evaluation. arXiv preprint\n  arXiv:2505.10793, 2025.\n\nShuyu Li, Yixiao Li, Zhiyu Wang, Yayao Zhang, Fei Wu, Oliver Deussen, Tong-Yee Lee, and\n  Weiming Dong. SongEcho: Towards cover song generation via instance-adaptive element-wise\n  linear modulation. In Proc. International Conference on Learning Representations (ICLR),\n  2026.\n\nYishan Lv, Jing Luo, Boyuan Ju, Yang Zhang, Xinda Wu, Bo Yuan, and Xinyu Yang. Song\n  aesthetics evaluation with multi-stem attention and hierarchical uncertainty modeling. In\n  Proc. International Society for Music Information Retrieval Conference (ISMIR), 2026. To\n  appear; arXiv:2601.12222.\n\nBrian McFee, Colin Raffel, Dawen Liang, Daniel P. W. Ellis, Matt McVicar, Eric Battenberg,\n  and Oriol Nieto. librosa: Audio and music signal analysis in Python. In Proc. 14th Python in\n  Science Conference (SciPy), pages 18–25, 2015.\n\nColin Raffel and Daniel P. W. Ellis. Intuitive analysis, creation and manipulation of MIDI data\n  with pretty_midi. In Proc. ISMIR Late Breaking/Demo Session, 2014.\n\nChristian Steinmetz. pyloudnorm: A simple implementation of ITU-R BS.1770-4 loudness algo-\n  rithm in Python. https://github.com/csteinmetz1/pyloudnorm, 2019.\n\nDan Wu et al. SongBench: A fine-grained multi-aspect benchmark for song quality assessment.\n arXiv preprint arXiv:2604.25937, 2026.\n\n\n\n\n                                              14\n\fA     Rule-Based Threshold Audit\nSection 5.5 describes the percentile-rule pilot’s threshold estimation. Because small-sample\noverlap can reverse the raw candidate order, every metric pair was reordered by its known\ndirection before assignment. Table 7 records the metric properties and direction-enforcement\npolicy. Exact per-fold cutpoint values are archived in the released JSON file.\n\nTable 7: Threshold audit: metric directions and reordering policy. “Raw candidates” are the\nseverity-1 median and severity-2 quartile estimated within each LOO fold. When small-sample\noverlap reverses the expected order, the pair is reordered by the known metric direction before\nassigning yellow/red decision regions.\n\n        Metric       Direction         Dim.     Assertion      Note\n        LLR          higher-is-worse   D1       yellow < red   Large values indicate implau-\n                                                               sible leaps\n        PS           higher-is-worse   D1       yellow < red   Large values indicate irregu-\n                                                               lar intervals\n        IKNR         lower-is-worse    D2, D3   yellow > red   Low values indicate off-key\n                                                               notes\n        KC           lower-is-worse    D3       yellow > red   Low values indicate weak\n                                                               tonal center\n        KCR          higher-is-worse   D3       yellow < red   High values indicate key in-\n                                                               stability\n        LUFS_dev     higher-is-worse   D5       yellow < red   Large       deviation    from\n                                                               −12 LUFS reference\n        LRA          lower-is-worse    D5       yellow > red   Low values indicate com-\n                                                               pressed dynamics\n        SC           lower-is-worse    D5       yellow > red   Low values indicate flat spec-\n                                                               tral profile\n\n   PR is excluded from the rule pilot because it is reported for reference only and is not used as a\ndiagnostic metric. The per-fold JSON archive retains both raw candidates and direction-ordered\ncutpoints for reproducibility.\n\n\nB    Inter-Dimension Correlation Matrix\nSection 6.3 reports that all ten pairwise inter-dimension correlations had uncorrected p < 0.01.\nTable 8 provides the complete ρ and p values.\n    The weakest association is D1–D4 (ρ = 0.507, p = 0.0042); the strongest is D3–D5 (ρ =\n0.799, p < 0.0001). The consistently positive structure indicates that model failures tend to\nco-occur, but the D3-high/D2-low asymmetric cases (Section 6.3) show that co-occurrence does\nnot make the dimensions interchangeable.\n\n\n\n\n                                                15\n\fTable 8: Pairwise Spearman rank correlations among the five diagnostic dimensions (n = 30).\nAll correlations are positive and significant at uncorrected p < 0.01. These values are exploratory\nand are not adjusted for multiplicity.\n\n                                     D1     D2        D3       D4       D5\n                               D1    —     .728       .727     .507     .761\n                               D2           —         .706     .631     .785\n                               D3                      —       .688     .799\n                               D4                               —       .771\n                               D5                                        —\n\n                                    Pair          ρ             p\n                                    D1–D2    0.728           < 0.0001\n                                    D1–D3    0.727           < 0.0001\n                                    D1–D4    0.507            0.0042\n                                    D1–D5    0.761           < 0.0001\n                                    D2–D3    0.706           < 0.0001\n                                    D2–D4    0.631            0.0002\n                                    D2–D5    0.785           < 0.0001\n                                    D3–D4    0.688           < 0.0001\n                                    D3–D5    0.799           < 0.0001\n                                    D4–D5    0.771           < 0.0001\n\n\n\n\n                                                  16\n\f", "numLines": 812, "startLine": 1, "totalLines": 812}}}
